  "local_port": 55918,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How is the Culinary Institute of America for international students?",
  "response": "The Culinary Institute of America (CIA) is one of the most prestigious culinary schools in the world, and it attracts a diverse student body, including many international students. Here\u2019s an overview of what international students can expect:\n\n### Academic Excellence\n- **Reputation**: CIA is globally recognized for its rigorous programs in culinary arts, baking and pastry arts, food business management, and hospitality management. Graduates often go on to successful careers in top restaurants, hotels, and food businesses around the world.\n- **Programs**: The CIA offers associate, bachelor\u2019s, and master\u2019s degree programs, as well as certificate programs. The curriculum is comprehensive, blending hands-on training with theoretical knowledge.\n\n### Support for International Students\n- **International Admissions**: The CIA has a dedicated international admissions team to assist with the application process, including visa requirements and documentation.\n- **English Language Proficiency**: Non-native English speakers are typically required to demonstrate proficiency through tests like TOEFL or IELTS. Some students may need to take additional English language courses.\n- **Orientation**: The CIA offers orientation programs specifically for international students to help them acclimate to life in the U.S. and the school\u2019s community.\n\n### Campus Life\n- **Diverse Community**: With students from around the world, the CIA offers a multicultural environment that enriches the learning experience.\n- **Student Services**: The school provides various support services, including academic advising, career services, and counseling, to help all students succeed.\n- **Extracurricular Activities**: Students can participate in a variety of clubs, organizations, and events that foster personal and professional growth.\n\n### Practical Experience\n- **Internships**: The CIA requires students to complete internships (externships) as part of their degree programs. These provide valuable real-world experience and networking opportunities.\n- **Global Opportunities**: The CIA has campuses in New York, California, and Texas, each offering unique learning environments and opportunities. Additionally, the school has partnerships with institutions and organizations worldwide, providing students with global perspectives and experiences.\n\n### Career Opportunities\n- **Alumni Network**: CIA graduates are part of a vast and influential alumni network, which can be a significant asset when seeking employment.\n- **Career Services**: The school\u2019s Career Services Department offers resources, job fairs, and recruitment events to help students launch their careers in the culinary and hospitality industries.\n\n### Financial Considerations\n- **Tuition and Fees**: The cost of attendance can be high, so international students should budget accordingly. The CIA offers some scholarships and financial aid options, though these may be more limited for international students.\n- **Living Expenses**: Students need to account for housing, meals, transportation, and other living expenses. The CIA provides resources to help students find suitable accommodation.\n\n### Cultural Adaptation\n- **Cultural Differences**: Adjusting to a new culture can be challenging, but the CIA\u2019s diverse and inclusive community helps ease this transition. Students are encouraged to share their culinary traditions and learn from others.\n\nOverall, the Culinary Institute of America offers a well-rounded and supportive environment for international students, combining top-tier culinary education with opportunities for personal and professional growth.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
